> Using nuts to thicken a sauce is a great trick to learn. It works for dishes from all around the world - Indian curries, Spanish soups, South American stews and many more. We're using almonds today to give a creamy texture and subtle flavour to this Greek-inspired stew. Served over herb-flecked couscous and topped with feta, you'd have to be nuts not to give it a go!

Preheat your oven to 200°C. Put the @water{250%ml} on to boil in a large #saucepan{} on medium heat. Add the @vegetable stock pot{1/2} and stir to dissolve. Remove the root and dark green tops from the @leek{1}, cut in half lengthways and thinly slice into half moons. Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Halve, peel and finely chop the @red onion{1/2}(peeled and finely chopped).

Add the @couscous{150%g} to your pan of stock, remove from the heat and pop on a #lid{}. Set it aside until everything else is ready. Halve the @aubergine{1} lengthways and chop into 1cm pieces. Put on a #baking tray{}, drizzle over some @olive oil{a drizzle} and season with a pinch of @salt{}. Toss to coat then spread out evenly and roast on the top shelf of your oven until soft and brown, ~{20%minutes}.

Put a splash of @olive oil{} in a #frying pan{} on medium-low heat. Add the leek, garlic and onion. Cook until soft, about ~{5%minutes}. Stir in the @tomato puree{15%g} and @tomato passata{1.5%tbsp} and continue to cook on low heat until the stew begins to thicken, ~{5-10%minutes}.

Add the @olives{30}, a pinch of @salt{} and a few grinds of @black pepper{} to the stew. Once the aubergine is cooked, add that in too along with the @ground almond{15%g}.

Pick the @basil{1/2}(leaves picked from stalks, finely chopped) from their stalks and finely chop (discard the stalks). Take the lid off the couscous and fluff it up with a #fork{}. Stir through three-quarters of the basil.

Serve the couscous with the aubergine stew on top. Crumble over the @feta cheese{1/2} and sprinkle on the remaining basil. Dinner time!